{{Infobox political party |name = Alliance for Justice and Democracy/Movement for Renewal |logo = |colorcode = #000000 |leader = |founder = [[Ibrahima Moctar Sarr]] |president = [[Ibrahima Moctar Sarr]] |chairman = |general_secretary = |first_secretary = |secretary_general = |presidium = |secretary = |spokesperson = |foundation = August 2007 |colors = Black and White |ideology = [[Black people|Black minority interests]] |headquarters = |international = |website = [http://www.ajd-mr.org/ www.ajd-mr.org] |country = Mauritania }}
The '''Alliance for Justice and Democracy/Movement for Renewal''' (''Alliance pour la Justice et la Démocratie/Mouvement pour la Rénovation'', '''AJD/MR''') is a [[political party]] in [[Mauritania]]. It represents the black minority population of the south of the country, centered on the [[Senegal River]] valley, and was formed and is led by rights activist and former presidential candidate [[Ibrahima Moctar Sarr]]. The party's colours are black and white, and its symbol is a [[Zebu]] bull, livestock being associated with the traditionally [[pastoralism|pastoralist]] [[Fula people]]<ref>{{lang-fr|Peul}}; {{lang-ff|Fulɓe}}</ref> who make up much of its constituency.<ref>[http://www.ajd-mr.org/modules/Dossiers/NosStatuts.pdf Nos Statuts] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817093940/http://ajd-mr.org/modules/Dossiers/NosStatuts.pdf |date=2013-08-17 }}: Statutes of the AJD/MR. accessed 2009-04-22</ref>
==Founding== The party was founded in August 2007 by a merger of [[Ibrahima Moctar Sarr]]'s [[Movement for National Reconciliation (Mauritania)|Movement for National Reconciliation]] and the [[Alliance for Justice and Democracy (Mauritania)|Alliance for Justice and Democracy (AJD)]] party, with Sarr elected as the leader of the new party. Sarr, a [[Serer people|Serer]] journalist, had been a high profile activist since the 1980s, and his party defined itself as campaigning for [[Civil rights|equal rights]] for [[Pulaar]]-speakers, [[Soninke people|Soninké]] and [[Wolof people|Wolof]] people alongside [[Moors]], and the return of Mauritanian [[refugee]]s from [[Senegal]].<ref name="ami.mr">[http://www.ami.mr/fr/articles/2007/mars/15/5.html "Le conseil constitutionnel proclame les résultats du premier tour de l'élection présidentielles du 11 mars 2007"]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Agence Mauritanienne d'Information, March 15, 2007 {{fr icon}}.</ref> Sarr had stood as an [[independent (politician)|independent]] in the [[Mauritanian presidential election, 2007|March 2007 presidential election]] on an anti-racist platform, came in fifth place with 7.95% in the first round<ref name="ami.mr"/> and supported [[Ahmed Ould Daddah]] for the second round.<ref>[http://apanews.net/apa.php?page=show_article_eng&id_article=23863 "Mauritania : Ould Daddah gets support of fifth place holder for presidential runoff"]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, African Press Agency, March 20, 2007.</ref>
==2008 break with government== On May 10, 2008 the AJD/MR announced they would not participate in the government of Prime Minister [[Yahya Ould Ahmed El Waghef]] due to policy differences.<ref>[http://www.ami.mr/fr/articles/2008/Mai/10/03.html "L'AJD/MR annonce qu'il ne participera au nouveau gouvernement"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514080556/http://www.ami.mr/fr/articles/2008/Mai/10/03.html |date=2008-05-14 }}, AMI, May 10, 2008 {{fr icon}}.</ref>
==2008 coup== Following the [[2008 Mauritanian coup|August 2008 military coup]], Sarr and the AJD/MR expressed support for the military junta. But on August 26, 2008, the AJD/MR, along with the [[Rally of Democratic Forces]] (RFD) and the [[Movement for Direct Democracy]] (MDD) all announced their decision to not participate in the Laghdaf's government<ref name=Three>[http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5hArWJ2Rue6z_YF7lrznr_ouXLD4w "Three parties refuse to join Mauritanian government"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520164929/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5hArWJ2Rue6z_YF7lrznr_ouXLD4w |date=2011-05-20 }}, AFP, August 26, 2008.</ref> because the junta had not clarified whether or not someone serving in the military would be allowed to stand as a presidential candidate<ref name=Three/><ref name=NewGov>[http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jPTnuP1yd3YB8MACszotPxb4akUg "Mauritanian junta announces formation of a government"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520164527/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jPTnuP1yd3YB8MACszotPxb4akUg |date=2011-05-20 }}, AFP, September 1, 2008.</ref> and had not specified how long it intended to remain in power.<ref name=NewGov/> The new government led by Laghdaf was appointed on August 31<ref name=NewGov/><ref name=Composition>[http://www.ami.mr/fr/articles/2008/Aout/31/11.html "Composition du nouveau gouvernement"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080904050204/http://www.ami.mr/fr/articles/2008/Aout/31/11.html |date=September 4, 2008 }}, AMI, August 31, 2008 {{fr icon}}.</ref>
==2009 elections== Sarr announced on 11 April 2009, that he would be the AJD/MR candidate in the controversial [[Mauritanian presidential election, 2009|June 2009 presidential election]], which was being organized by the junta and which opposition parties were planning to boycott. Sarr said that "the conditions are there for a free poll" and that Mauritania did not have democracy under Abdallahi's presidency.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iUVGcFo7Gw9AcISVJyQfhcnoS83A "Pro-coup leader to stand in Mauritania presidential poll"], AFP, 11 April 2009.</ref>
