 |last=Tripp|first=Aili|title=Global Feminism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6TwKgIaOLqgC&pg=PA55|accessdate=2014-11-21 |date=2006-07-01|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-2794-2}} {{refend}} {{Authority control}} {{DEFAULTSORT:Association internationale des femmes}} [[Category:Feminist organizations]] [[Category:Women's rights organizations]] [[Category:Former international organizations]] [[Category:Pacifist feminism]] [[Category:Peace organizations]] [[Category:Organizations established in 1868]] [[Category:Organizations disestablished in 1872]] [[Category:Organisations based in Geneva]] [[Category:1868 establishments in Switzerland]] [[Category:1872 disestablishments]]

{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}} {{Infobox civilian attack | title = Bodo League massacre | image = Execution of South Korean political prisoners by the South Korean military and police at Daejeon, South Korea, over several days in July 1950.jpg | caption = Summary execution of South Korean political prisoners by the South Korean military and police at Daejeon, South Korea | location = [[Korea]] | target = Communists and suspected Communist sympathizers{{sfn|Kim|2004|p=533}} | date = Summer of 1950 | time = | timezone = | type = [[Massacre]] | fatalities = 100,000<ref name="smh20081114" />–200,000<ref>https://books.google.com.sg/books?id=zVxeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT73#v=onepage&q&f=false</ref> | injuries = | perps = South Korean anticommunists | motive = [[Anti-communism]]; fear of [[North Korea]]n collaborators }}
The '''Bodo League massacre''' ({{korean|hangul=보도연맹 학살사건|hanja=保導聯盟虐殺事件}}) was a [[massacre]] and [[war crime]] against [[Communism|communists]] and suspected sympathizers (many of whom were civilians who had no connection with communism or communists) that occurred in the summer of 1950 during the [[Korean War]]. Estimates of the death toll vary. It has been estimated that the number of victims killed is between 100,000 and 200,000.<ref name="smh20081114">[http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/south-korea-owns-up-to-brutal-past/2008/11/14/1226318928410.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1 South Korea owns up to brutal past] Sydney Morning Herald</ref> The number of Bodo League members killed in [[Ulsan]], [[Cheongdo County]] and [[Kimhae]] alone, where the number of confirmed victims was almost exactly 4,934, was 30 to 70 percent of the press alliance members massacred and more than 100 people to more than 1,000 people were killed in each county unit respectively.<ref>진실화해위는 확인된 희생자 수만 4천934명으로 거의 정확하게 희생자 수가 밝혀진 울산ㆍ청도ㆍ김해 지역은 보도연맹원 가운데 30~70%가 학살됐고 각 군 단위에서 적게는 100여명, 많게는 1천여명이 살해된 것으로 추정된다고 밝혔다.{{cite news|url=http://v.media.daum.net/v/20091126115504424|title=진실화해위, 보도연맹원 4천934명 희생 확인(종합)|language=ko}}</ref> The massacre was wrongly blamed on the communists.<ref name="smh_1226318928410"/> For four decades the South Korean government concealed this massacre. Survivors were forbidden by the government from revealing it, under suspicion of being communist sympathizers. Public revelation carried with it the threat of torture and death. During the 1990s and onwards, several corpses were excavated from mass graves, resulting in public awareness of the massacre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=055&aid=0000171996|title=진실화해위 "보도연맹원 4천934명 희생 확인" : 네이버 뉴스|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsis.com/ar_detail/view.html/?ar_id=NISX20140623_0013000775&cID=10806&pID=10800|title=:: 공감언론 뉴시스통신사 ::|last=NEWSIS|website=newsis|language=ko|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>
==Bodo League== [[File:국민보도연맹증.jpg|National Bodo League members identity card|left|National Bodo League members identity card|thumb|180px]]
<!--Please add the year-->South Korean President [[Syngman Rhee]] had about 300,000 suspected communist sympathizers or his political opponents enrolled in an official "re-education" movement known as the ''Bodo League'' (or National Rehabilitation and Guidance League, National Guard Alliance,<ref name=hani100123/> National Guidance Alliance<ref name=cbs-20090211/> National Bodo League,<ref name=hani070625/> Bodo Yeonmaeng,<ref name=hani100123/> Gukmin Bodo Ryeonmaeng, 국민보도연맹, 國民保導聯盟) on the pretext of protecting them from execution.<ref name="smh_1226318928410">{{cite web |year=2007 |url = http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/south-korea-owns-up-to-brutal-past/2008/11/14/1226318928410.html|title = South Korea owns up to brutal past|work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]]| accessdate = 2008-12-15}}</ref><ref name=hani100123/><ref name=kt20090203>{{cite news | url = http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2009/03/117_40555.html | title = Gov't Killed 3,400 Civilians During War | newspaper = [[Korea Times]] | author = Bae Ji-sook | date = 3 February 2009 | accessdate = 2011-07-18 }}</ref> The Bodo League was created by Korean jurists who had collaborated with the Japanese.<ref name="John Tirman 2011 96">{{cite book|author= John Tirman|title=The Deaths of Others: The Fate of Civilians in America's Wars|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x3n3Eq1eiBEC|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=96}}</ref> Non-communist sympathizers and others were also forced into the Bodo League to fill enlistment quotas.<ref name=hani070625>{{cite news | url = http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/218141.html | title = Waiting for the truth – A missed deadline contributes to a lost history | newspaper = [[Hankyoreh]] | date = 25 June 2007 | accessdate = 2010-07-22 }}</ref><ref name=kt20090203/>
In June 1949 the South Korean government accused independence activists of being members of the Bodo League.<ref name=hani100123>{{cite news | url = http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/427055.html | title = Family tragedy indicative of S. Korea's remaining war wounds – Kim Gwang-ho is waiting for the government to apologize for state crimes committed against his father and grandfather | newspaper = [[Hankyoreh]] | date = 23 January 2010 | accessdate = 2010-07-22 }}</ref> In 1950, just before the outbreak of the [[Korean War]], the first president of [[South Korea]], Syngman Rhee, had about 20,000 alleged communists imprisoned.{{sfn|Kim|2004|p=526}}
==Executions== [[File:Prisoners on ground before execution,Taejon, South Korea.jpg|thumb|Prisoners lie on the ground before execution by South Korean troops near Daejon, South Korea, July 1950. Photo by U.S. Army Maj. Abbott.<ref name="apphoto">{{cite news |url= http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/jul/10/korea-bloodbath-probe-ends-us-escapes-much-blame/ |title=Korea bloodbath probe ends; US escapes much blame |work=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=San Diego Union Tribune |author=Charles J. Hanley & Hyung-Jin Kim | date =10 July 2010 |accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref>]] [[File:South Korean soldiers walk among dead political prisoners, Taejon, South Korea.jpg|thumb|South Korean soldiers walk among bodies of South Korean political prisoners shot near Daejon, South Korea, July 1950. Photo by U.S. Army Major Abbott.<ref name="apphoto"/>]]
Under the leadership of [[Kim Il-sung]], the [[Korean People's Army]] attacked from the north on 25 June 1950, starting the Korean War.<ref name="Stokesbury1990">{{cite book |title= A Short History of the Korean War |last=Stokesbury |first= James L |year= 1990 |publisher=Harper Perennial |location= New York |isbn= 0-688-09513-5}}</ref> According to Kim Mansik, who was a military police superior officer, President [[Syngman Rhee]] ordered the execution of people related to either the Bodo League or the [[South Korean Workers Party]] on 27 June 1950.<ref name=hani100625>{{cite news | url = http://h21.hani.co.kr/arti/special/special_general/27607.html | script-title=ko:60년 만에 만나는 한국의 신들러들 | newspaper = [[Hankyoreh]] | date = 25 June 2010 | accessdate = 2010-07-14 | language = Korean }}</ref><ref name=omn070704>{{cite news |url=http://www.ohmynews.com/NWS_Web/View/at_pg.aspx?CNTN_CD=A0000420451 |script-title=ko:"보도연맹 학살은 이승만 특명에 의한 것" 민간인 처형 집행했던 헌병대 간부 최초증언 출처 : "보도연맹 학살은 이승만 특명에 의한 것" – 오마이뉴스 |newspaper=[[Ohmynews]] |date=4 July 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-14 |language=Korean |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110503211221/http://www.ohmynews.com/NWS_Web/View/at_pg.aspx?CNTN_CD=A0000420451 |archivedate=3 May 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> The first massacre was started one day later in [[Hoengseong]], [[Gangwon-do (South Korea)|Gangwon-do]] on 28 June.<ref name=omn070704/><ref name=cbs070704>{{cite news | url = http://www.cbs.co.kr/nocut/show.asp?idx=556349 | script-title=ko:헌병대의 보도연맹원 '대량학살' 최초 구체증언 확보 6.25 당시 헌병대 과장 김만식 씨 증언 토대, 전국 조직적 학살 자행 | newspaper = [[CBS]] | date = 4 July 2007 | accessdate = 2010-07-14 | language = Korean }}</ref> Retreating South Korean forces and anti-communist groups<ref name="name">{{cite web |date=17 November 2003|url = http://www.asianresearch.org/articles/1636.html|title = The left-right confrontation in Korea – Its origin|publisher = asianresearch.org| accessdate = 2008-12-15 | last= Kim Young Sik|quote=}}</ref> executed the alleged communist prisoners, along with many of the Bodo League members.<ref name="smh_1226318928410"/> The executions were performed without any trials or sentencing.<ref name=bbc000421>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/721616.stm | title = New evidence of Korean war killings | newspaper = [[BBC]] | date = 21 April 2000 | accessdate = 2010-07-23 }}</ref> Kim Tae Sun, the chief of the Seoul Metropolitan Police, admitted to personally executing at least 12 "communists and suspected communists" after the outbreak of the war.{{sfn|Kim|2004|p=534}} When Seoul was recaptured in late September 1950, an estimated 30,000 South Koreans were summarily deemed collaborators with the North Koreans and shot by ROK forces.<ref name="John Tirman 2011 98">{{cite book|author= John Tirman|title=The Deaths of Others: The Fate of Civilians in America's Wars|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x3n3Eq1eiBEC|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=98}}</ref> At least one US lieutenant colonel is known to have approved the executions, when he told a South Korean colonel that he could kill a large number of prisoners in [[Busan]] if the North Korean troops approached. A mass execution of 3,400 South Koreans did indeed take place near Busan that summer.<ref name="John Tirman 2011 97">{{cite book|author= John Tirman|title=The Deaths of Others: The Fate of Civilians in America's Wars|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x3n3Eq1eiBEC|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=97}}</ref>
United States official documents show that American officers witnessed and photographed the massacre.<ref name=bbc000421/> In one case a US officer is known to have sanctioned the killing of political prisoners so that they would not fall into enemy hands.<ref name="smh_1226318928410"/><ref name="Fox">{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/printer_friendly_wires/2008Dec07/0,4675,ASKoreaMassExecutions,00.html |title=Children 'executed' in 1950 South Korean killings |work=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]] |author=Charles J. Hanley and Jae-soon Chang |date=7 December 2008 |accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref> In another, United States official documents show that [[John J. Muccio]], then [[United States Ambassador to Korea|United States Ambassador to South Korea]], made recommendations to [[South Korean President]] [[Rhee Syngman]] and [[Defense Minister]] [[Shin Sung-mo]] that the executions be stopped.<ref name=bbc000421/> American witnesses also reported the scene of the execution of a girl who appeared to be 12 or 13 years old.<ref name=cbs-20090211/><ref name=bbc000421/> The massacre was also reported to both [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] and Gen. [[Douglas MacArthur]],<ref name="smh_1226318928410"/> who described it as an "internal matter".<ref name="John Tirman 2011 98"/><ref name="Paul M. Edwards 2010 33">{{cite book|author=Paul M. Edwards|title=Historical Dictionary of the Korean War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=scZN59DXeOwC|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press Inc|page=33}}</ref> According to one witness, 40 victims had their backs broken with rifle butts and were shot later. Victims in seaside villages were tied together and thrown into the sea to drown.<ref name="John Tirman 2011 97"/> Retired South Korean Adm. [[Nam Sang-hui]] confessed that he authorized 200 victims' bodies to be thrown into the sea, saying, "There was no time for trials for them."<ref name=bbc000421/>
There were also British and Australian witnesses.<ref name="smh_1226318928410"/><ref name="hani090303">{{cite web |accessdate=2010-07-13|url = http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_national/341888.html|title = Truth commission confirms Korean War killings by soldiers and police 3,400 civilians and inmates were shot dead or drowned out of concerns they might cooperate with the People's Army | publisher = [[Hankyoreh]] | date = 3 March 2009}}</ref> Great Britain raised this issue with the U.S. at a diplomatic level, causing [[Dean Rusk]], [[Assistant Secretary of State for Far Eastern Affairs]], to inform the British that U.S. commanders were doing "everything they can to curb such atrocities".<ref name=cbs-20090211>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/07/05/national/main4234885.shtml |title=U.S. Allowed Korean Massacre In 1950 |author=Writers Charles J. Hanley and Jae-Soon Chang |work=Associated Press |publisher=CBS |date=11 February 2009 |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> During the massacre, the British protected their allies and saved some citizens.<ref name=bbc080818/><ref name=cbs090211>{{cite news | url = http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-201_162-4234885.html?pageNum=2&tag=contentMain;contentBody | title = AP: U.S. Allowed Korean Massacre In 1950 | newspaper = [[CBS News]] (AP) | author = Writers Charles J. Hanley and Jae-Soon Chang | date = 11 February 2009 | accessdate = 4 June 2012 }}</ref>
==Aftermath== After the UN offensive in which South Korea recovered its occupied territories, the police and militia groups executed suspected North Korean sympathizers. In October 1950, the [[Goyang Geumjeong Cave Massacre]] occurred. In December, [[British troops]] saved civilians lined up to be shot by South Korean officers and seized one execution site outside [[Seoul]] to prevent further massacres.<ref name=cbs-20090211/><ref name=bbc080818>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7567936.stm | title = Unearthing proof of Korea killings | newspaper = [[BBC]] | date = 18 August 2008 | accessdate = 2010-07-23 }}</ref> On January 4, 1951, the [[Ganghwa massacre]] was committed by South Korean police, who killed 139 civilians in an effort to prevent their collaboration with the North Koreans. According to a South Korean report, South Korea and the U.S. "aided right-wing civil organizations, such as the Ganghwa Self-defense Forces, by providing combat equipment and supplies."<ref>{{cite web|title=Truth and Reconciliation: Activities of the Past Three Years|url=http://www.jinsil.go.kr/pdf/%EC%98%81%EB%AC%B8%EB%B0%B1%EC%84%9C_20MS%ED%8C%8C%EC%9D%BC_0205.pdf|website=Truth and Reconciliation Commission, Republic of Korea|publisher=Truth and Reconciliation Commission, Republic of Korea|accessdate=30 January 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303171441/http://jinsil.go.kr/pdf/%EC%98%81%EB%AC%B8%EB%B0%B1%EC%84%9C_20MS%ED%8C%8C%EC%9D%BC_0205.pdf|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{rp|74–75}}
==Truth and Reconciliation Commission==
{{Main|Truth and Reconciliation Commission (South Korea)}}
In 2008, trenches containing the bodies of children were discovered in [[Daejeon]], [[South Korea]], and other sites.<ref name="Fox"/>{{failed verification|date=June 2013}}<ref name="apphoto" /> South Korea's Truth and Reconciliation Commission documented testimonies of those still alive and who took part in the executions, including former Daejeon prison guard Lee Joon-young.
Besides photographs of the execution trench sites, the National Archives in Washington D.C. released declassified photographs of U.S. soldiers at execution sites including Daejeon, confirming American military knowledge.<ref name="Fox"/>{{Failed verification|date=June 2013}}<!-- The article states that “. . . declassified U.S. military documents show U.S. Army officers took photos of the assembly line-style executions outside the central city of Daejeon . . .”, not that the photos themselves have been released by the National Archives. -->
